{"id":"2107.09714","submitter":"Grgur Palle","authors":"Grgur Palle, D. K. Sunko","title":"Physical limitations of the Hohenberg-Mermin-Wagner theorem","comments":"This version (v2) is the authors' version which was accepted for\n  publication. The previous version (v1), which was never submitted itself,\n  contains additional material which some readers may find interesting","journal-ref":"J. Phys. A: Math. Theor. 54, 315001 (2021)","doi":"10.1088/1751-8121/ac0a9d","report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.stat-mech cond-mat.supr-con","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  The Hohenberg-Mermin-Wagner (HMW) theorem states that infrared (IR)\nfluctuations prevent long-range order which breaks continuous symmetries in two\ndimensions (2D), at finite temperatures. We note that the theorem becomes\nphysically effective for superconductivity (SC) only for astronomical sample\nsizes, so it does not prevent 2D SC in practice. We systematically explore the\nsensitivity of the magnetic and SC versions of the theorem to finite-size and\ndisorder effects. For magnetism, finite-size effects, disorder, and\nperpendicular coupling can all restore the order parameter at a non-negligible\nvalue of $T_c$ equally well, making the physical reason for finite $T_c$\nsample-dependent. For SC, an alternative version of the HMW theorem is\npresented, in which the temperature cutoff is set by Cooper pairing, in place\nof the Fermi energy in the standard version. It still allows 2D SC at $2$--$3$\ntimes the room temperature when the interaction scale is large and Cooper pairs\nare small, the case with high-$T_c$ SC in the cuprates. Thus IR fluctuations do\nnot prevent 2D SC at room temperatures in samples of any reasonable size, by\nany known version of the HMW argument. A possible approach to derive\nmechanism-dependent upper bounds for SC $T_c$ is pointed out.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 20 Jul 2021 18:35:55 GMT"},{"version":"v2","cre